Dramatic Cost Reduction:** Starship is designed for full and rapid reusability. The company believes it can **reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more** compared to NASA\'s historical average of $18,500 per kilogram.\n2.  **Step-Function Capability Increase:** It is designed to enable a **"step-function change"** in launch capability:\n    *   **Reusability:** It aims to be the world\'s first fully, rapidly reusable launch vehicle, enabling a high launch cadence (potentially multiple times per day).\n    *   **Payload Capacity:** Starship V3 is designed for **100 metric tons** to orbit, with future generations targeting **200 metric tons**.\n3.  **Enabling New Revenue Streams:** The breakthrough in cost and capacity is expected to:\n    *   Unlock **entirely new categories of missions**.\n    *   Provide the foundational capacity to scale the **Starlink** broadband and mobile constellations (Connectivity segment).\n    *   Accelerate the deployment of **orbital AI compute** (AI segment).\n    *   Enable the development of a **lunar economy** and eventual missions to Mars.\n4.  **Financial Impact Transition:** While Starship R&D is currently depressing Space segment profitability, the company anticipates that:\n    *   R&D expenses will **moderate** after commercialization.\n    *   Starship will become a **larger contributor to launch volume**, shifting the business mix.\n    *   Improved economics will benefit both internal and third-party customers, reinforcing competitive advantages.\n\nIn summary, Starship represents a major, capital-intensive bet on radically lowering launch costs and expanding capabilities. The expected payoff is a transformation of the company\'s space segment from a launch service provider into the enabling platform for large-scale satellite networks, orbital infrastructure, and deep-space commerce.',
