    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Forward-Looking Statements & Growth Expectations for the Connectivity Segment\n\nBelow is a comprehensive extraction from all provided document chunks.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Revenue Growth Expectations\n\n| Metric | 2025 vs. 2024 | Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 | 2024 vs. 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Connectivity Revenue** | +$3,788M (+49.8%) | +$782M (+31.6%) | +$3,730M (+96.4%) |\n| **Income from Operations** | +$2,417M to $4,423M (+120.4%) | +$155M to $1,188M | +$1,537M to $2,006M |\n| **Segment Adj. EBITDA** | +$3,319M to $7,168M (+86.2%) | +$469M to $2,087M | +$2,247M to $3,849M |\n\n**Forward-Looking Statement (Revenue Drivers):**\n> *"We expect revenue from consumer subscribers, as well as enterprise and government customers, to be **the primary driver of Connectivity segment growth**, and that **Starlink Mobile will become a significant new contributor** of Connectivity revenue."*\n\n---\n\n## 2. Subscriber Growth Targets\n\n### Historical Trajectory\n- **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** Starlink Subscribers grew **104.7%**\n- **2025 vs. 2024:** Starlink Subscribers grew **99.9%**\n- **2024 vs. 2023:** Starlink Subscribers grew **96.5%**\n\n### Current Base (as of March 31, 2026)\n- **~10.3 million** Starlink Subscribers\n- Across **164 countries, territories, and markets** (collectively home to >3.3 billion people)\n- **>9,600** Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit\n\n### Forward-Looking Growth Strategies\nThe company outlined specific levers to drive **"meaningful subscriber growth"**:\n\n1. **Distribution Expansion:** Expanding the consumer distribution network across **thousands of authorized retail stores globally**\n2. **Marketing:** Executing **region-specific marketing campaigns** to increase brand awareness\n3. **Product Differentiation:** Clearly demonstrating Starlink\'s **superior speed, low-latency, and ease of installation**\n4. **Brand & Reliability:** Leveraging proven performance in rural, remote, and disaster-affected areas to reinforce Starlink\'s reputation as **"essential infrastructure"**, leading to higher adoption in new markets\n\n---\n\n## 3. ARPU Expectations (Declining Trend)\n\n| Period | ARPU Change | Primary Drivers |\n|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025 | **−22.9%** | International expansion; lower-priced service plans |\n| 2025 vs. 2024 | **−11.2%** | International expansion; lower-priced service plans |\n| 2024 vs. 2023 | **−8.1%** | International expansion |\n\n> **Forward-Looking Implication:** The company expects continued ARPU dilution as a trade-off for subscriber base expansion through international markets and tiered pricing. This is explicitly embedded in every forward period\'s commentary as a structural offset to subscriber growth.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Enterprise & Government Growth\n\n### Historical Drivers\n| Period | Enterprise/Government Revenue Increase | Key Components |\n|---|---|---|\n| **2025 vs. 2024** | +$1,411M | Enterprise connectivity +$1,218M (incl. mobile +$632M); Government +$193M |\n| **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025** | +$126M | Aviation/maritime/enterprise +$209M; Mobile +$85M; **Partially offset** by government decline of −$175M |\n| **2024 vs. 2023** | +$1,717M | Enterprise +$466M; Government +$1,250M |\n\n### Forward-Looking Statement (Enterprise)\n> *"We see a **large opportunity to grow the enterprise connectivity market** by providing solutions that had not previously existed."*\n\nGrowth verticals explicitly called out:\n- **Aviation**\n- **Maritime**\n- **Mobility**\n- **Government/Starshield** (secure satellite network for national security)\n- **Starlink Mobile** (revenue-sharing arrangements with MNO partners)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Profitability & Efficiency Expectations\n\n### Network Efficiency\n> *"We have driven our strong sequential Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA growth by **expanding the scale and efficiency of our LEO satellite constellations** and our **highly verticalized supply chain** and operating performance of our Connectivity segment, enabling us to onboard new users while **improving service quality**."*\n\n### EBITDA Growth Drivers (Forward-Looking)\nThe company attributes Adjusted EBITDA growth to:\n- **Higher revenue** from consumer and enterprise customer growth\n- **Scale benefits** from the LEO constellation\n- **Vertical integration** efficiencies\n\n**Partially offset by:**\n- Higher **marketing and international expansion costs** to grow subscribers\n- Higher **R&D costs for next-generation product development**\n\n---\n\n## 6. Cost & Investment Expectations\n\n### Rising Cost Drivers (Forward-Looking)\n\n| Cost Category | Details |\n|---|---|\n| **Depreciation** | Expected to increase due to **capitalized launch and satellite costs** from higher Starlink flight cadence |\n| **Ground Operations** | Higher ground operating costs (+$50M Q1 2026), customer support/installation (+$42M), payment processing (+$19M), freight (+$15M), warranty (+$12M) |\n| **International Expansion** | Higher operating expenses to **support and drive subscriber growth** in new markets |\n| **R&D** | Next-generation satellite production, Starlink Kits, and ground equipment development |\n| **Marketing** | Increased spend to **drive subscriber growth** and brand awareness |\n\n### Capital Expenditures\n- Q1 2026: Connectivity capex was **$1,332 million**\n- 2025: Connectivity capex reported (amount referenced in context of all segments)\n\n---\n\n## 7. Total Addressable Market (TAM) & Market Assumptions\n\nThe company\'s Connectivity market estimates are built on:\n\n> *"Our connectivity market estimates are based in part on estimates of the **number of households, businesses, aircraft and maritime vessels globally** derived from third-party sources, together with assumptions regarding **ARPU and monthly service revenue** derived from third-party industry data and our **internal expectations regarding pricing, adoption rates and service penetration** across different geographic regions and economic environments."*\n\n**Key caveat (risk disclosure):**\n> *"The estimates of future market opportunity and forecasts of market growth, and our ability to capture such markets, included in this prospectus **may prove to be inaccurate**."*\n\n---\n\n## 8. Regulatory & Adoption Risks\n\n| Risk | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Licensing** | Requires authorizations from FCC (US) and international telecom regulators; described as **"complex and time-consuming"** |\n| **Spectrum Access** | **"Limited and highly regulated"** |\n| **Market Acceptance** | Growth depends on ability to **"increase market awareness and acceptance of connectivity through Starlink across numerous international markets, each with its unique challenges"** |\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Forward-Looking Expectations at a Glance\n\n| Category | Expectation |\n|---|---|\n| **Primary Revenue Drivers** | Consumer subscribers + Enterprise/Government customers |\n| **New Revenue Stream** | Starlink Mobile expected to become **significant** contributor |\n| **Subscriber Growth** | Continued aggressive growth via retail expansion, marketing, and product differentiation |\n| **ARPU** | Continued decline due to international expansion and lower-priced plans |\n| **Enterprise Growth** | Large untapped opportunity in aviation, maritime, mobility, government |\n| **Profitability** | EBITDA growth driven by scale, vertical integration, and network efficiency |\n| **Cost Pressures** | Rising depreciation (satellites/launches), R&D (next-gen), marketing, and international expansion |\n| **TAM Basis** | Global households, businesses, aircraft, maritime vessels; ARPU/penetration assumptions |\n| **Key Risks** | Regulatory delays, spectrum constraints, market acceptance variance, TAM estimation accuracy |',
