 at $(351M)).\n2. **Starship as the transformational catalyst**: Designed to reduce cost to orbit by 99%, enable airline-like reusability (multiple launches per day), and serve as the physical enabler for both Starlink expansion and orbital AI compute.\n\n### Forward vs. Present Dependence\nThe Space segment sits in the middle of the spectrum. Its present economics are deteriorating (Adj. EBITDA down 43% from FY24 to FY25, now negative in Q1 2026) due to $3B+/year in Starship R&D. The forward narrative—Starship commercialization in H2 2026, cost revolution, enabling new mission categories—is necessary to justify continued capital allocation, but the segment already has a demonstrated operational track record (165 launches/year). **The forward story extends and transforms an existing business rather than creating one from scratch.**\n\n---\n\n## 2. CONNECTIVITY SEGMENT — "The Proven Profit Engine"\n\n### Presently Disclosed Economics\n\n| Metric | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue ($M) | $3,869 | $7,599 | $11,387 | $2,475 | $3,257 |\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA ($M) | $1,602 | $3,849 | $7,168 | $1,618 | $2,087 |\n| Adj. EBITDA Margin | 41.4% | 50.7% | 63.0% | 65.4% | 64.1% |\n| Starlink Subscribers (M) | 2.3 | 4.4 | 8.9 | 5.0 | 10.3 |\n| ARPU ($/month) | $99 | $91 | $81 | $86 | $66 |\n| Satellites in Orbit | — | — | — | — | ~9,600 |\n| Satellite-to-Mobile Unique Devices | — | — | — | — | 7.4M |\n\n### KPIs Disclosed\n- **Subscriber growth**: 2.3M → 10.3M over ~3 years (~100% YoY growth consistently).\n- **ARPU**: Declining steadily from $99/mo to $66/mo, driven by international expansion and lower-priced plans.\n- **Revenue composition**: Consumer ($2,148M Q1 2026) vs. Enterprise & Government ($1,109M Q1 2026).\n- **Revenue CAGR** (FY23→FY25): ~71.3% over two years—explosive growth.\n- **Adj. EBITDA CAGR** (FY23→FY25): ~111.6% over two years—operating leverage at work.\n\n### Investment Narrative\nConnectivity is framed as a rapidly scaling, high-margin business validating SpaceX\'s vertical integration model:\n\n1. **Subscriber expansion**: The 10.3M subscriber base across 164 countries, with distribution expanding through thousands of retail stores.\n2. **Enterprise/government growth**: Aviation, maritime, mobility, and Starshield (secure government network) represent "large untapped opportunity."\n3. **Starlink Mobile**: Satellite-to-mobile service with MNO revenue-sharing is expected to become a "significant new contributor."\n4. **Operating leverage**: Adj. EBITDA margin expanded from 41% to 64%, driven by scale efficiencies in the LEO constellation and vertical supply chain.\n\n### Forward vs. Present Dependence\n**Connectivity is the segment most grounded in presently disclosed economics.** The present financials tell a compelling, self-contained story: 194% revenue growth and 347% EBITDA growth over two years, with 64% Adj. EBITDA margins already achieved. The forward narrative—continued subscriber growth, enterprise expansion, Starlink Mobile—is an extrapolation of already-proven dynamics. ARPU dilution is a disclosed structural trade-off, but revenue growth has more than offset it. The segment does not depend on unproven technologies or speculative market creation to justify its current trajectory.\n\n---\n\n## 3. AI SEGMENT — "A Bet on a $26.5 Trillion Future"\n\n### Presently Disclosed Economics\n\n| Metric | FY 2023 | FY 2024 | FY 2025 | Q1 2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue ($M) | $2,961 | $2,620 | $3,201 | $727 | $818 |\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA ($M) | $1,222 | $347 | $(1,237) | $(112) | $(609) |\n| Adj. EBITDA Margin | 41.3% | 13.2% | −38.6% | −15.4% | −74.4% |\n| R&D Expense ($M) | — | — | $5,064 | — | — |\n| Capital Expenditures ($M) | — | — | $12,727 | — | $7,723 |\n| Nameplate Compute Draw (GW) | 0.0 | 0.3 | 0.8 | 0.3 | 1.0 |\n\n### KPIs Disclosed\n- **Revenue CAGR** (FY23→FY25): ~4.0% over two years—essentially flat.\n- **Nameplate Compute Draw**: 0 GW (FY23) → 1.0 GW (Q1 2026)—infrastructure scaling rapidly.\n- **Capital intensity**: Q1 2026 CapEx of $7,723M was **9.4x quarterly revenue** of $818M.\n- **Revenue composition**: Advertising ($343M Q1 2026) and AI Solutions & Infrastructure ($475M Q1 2026).\n- **User base**: ~550 million monthly active AI users (disclosed as a forward metric, not a revenue-linked KPI).\n- **Total CapEx** (FY25 + Q1 2026): $20.45 billion invested in compute infrastructure.\n\n### Investment Narrative\nThe AI segment\'s equity story rests almost entirely on forward expectations:\n\n1. **$26.5 trillion TAM**: AI Infrastructure ($2.4T), Enterprise Applications ($22.7T), Consumer Subscriptions ($760B), Digital Advertising ($600B).\n2. **Orbital AI compute**: Plans to deploy AI compute satellites in space "as early as 2028," targeting 100 GW of space-based compute per year—leveraging space-based solar power to overcome terrestrial energy constraints.\n3. **Multi-year investment horizon**: Management explicitly acknowledges the segment will not achieve "sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA" for years.\n4. **Grok/X ecosystem**: 550M MAU provides a distribution platform, but monetization remains early.\n\n### Forward vs. Present Dependence — THE CRITICAL DISTINCTION\n\nThe AI segment\'s present economics tell a story of **accelerating deterioration**:\n- Revenue essentially flat from FY2023 ($2.96B) to FY2025 ($3.20B)—only +8%.\n- Adj. EBITDA swung from +$1.2B (FY23) to −$1.2B (FY25)—a $2.5B negative swing.\n- Q1 2026 Adj. EBITDA margin is −74.4%, meaning for every $1 of revenue, the segment loses $0.74.\n- Capital consumption dwarfs revenue generation: $20.4B in CapEx over 5 quarters produced only $4.7B in cumulative revenue.\n- The filing concedes that orbital AI compute involves "significant technical complexity, unproven technologies or technologies that do not exist."\n\n**The equity story for AI cannot be told with presently disclosed economics.** Every element of the investment thesis—TAM capture, orbital compute, sustained profitability—lies in the future. The present KPIs (compute draw scaling, user count) measure infrastructure buildout, not economic returns.\n\n---\n\n## Comparative Assessment: Forward Expectation Dependence\n\n| Dimension | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue growth (FY23→FY25) | +14.9% | +194.3% | +8.1% |\n| Adj. EBITDA growth (FY23→FY25) | −34.5% | +347.4% | n/m (swing to loss) |\n| Current Adj. EBITDA margin (Q1 2026) | −56.7% | +64.1% | −74.4% |\n| Proven operational KPIs | Launch cadence ✓ | Subscribers, ARPU ✓ | Compute draw (infrastructure only) |\n| Forward narrative depends on… | Starship commercialization | Continued subscriber/enterprise growth | Unproven orbital compute, $26.5T TAM |\n| Filing acknowledges unproven tech? | No (Falcon/Dragon proven) | No (Starlink proven) | **Yes** ("technologies that do not exist") |\n| Years to positive EBITDA (per filing) | Near-term (post-Starship) | Already positive | **"Multi-year investment horizon"** |\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\n**The AI segment\'s equity story relies most heavily on forward expectations rather than presently disclosed economics.**\n\nThe Connectivity segment can be valued on current cash flows: $7.2B in Adj. EBITDA at 63% margins with 100%+ subscriber growth. The Space segment has a proven operational foundation under temporary R&D-driven margin pressure. The AI segment, by contrast, presents:\n\n- **Flat revenue** (+8% over two years)\n- **Deepening losses** (Adj. EBITDA from +$1.2B to −$1.2B)\n- **Extraordinary capital consumption** ($20.4B CapEx against $4.7B revenue over 5 quarters)\n- **An investment thesis built on**: a $26.5T TAM addressable only through orbital AI compute using "technologies that do not exist," with deployment "as early as 2028"\n\nThe filing\'s own cautionary language—"multi-year investment horizon," "technologies that do not exist," "may take longer to execute than anticipated," and "may ultimately be unsuccessful"—underscores that the AI segment\'s valuation must be anchored almost entirely in forward expectations. Presently disclosed economics provide essentially no support for the equity narrative.\n\n---\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 Filing (May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n'
